WEBVTT

00:01.958 --> 00:04.221
LAINEY: Back in the '90s,
we had a ton of toy crazes,

00:04.308 --> 00:07.398
but the biggest of them all
was Tamagotchi.

00:07.485 --> 00:09.444
Long before we could
play every game
imaginable on our phones,

00:09.531 --> 00:11.881
all we had were these
digital babies.

00:11.968 --> 00:13.448
[DEVICE BEEPS]
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

00:13.535 --> 00:14.797
Tom Scott!
Get your head in the game!

00:14.884 --> 00:16.538
[DEVICE BEEPING]

00:16.625 --> 00:19.541
School is for dodge ball
and sometimes books,
not toys.

00:19.628 --> 00:21.151
[DEVICE BEEPS]
The hell is this thing?

00:21.238 --> 00:22.239
It's a Tamagotchi.

00:22.326 --> 00:24.807
[DEVICES BEEPING]

00:26.983 --> 00:28.854
COACH MELLOR: My God,
they're everywhere.

00:28.941 --> 00:30.639
All right, 10 laps!
All of you!

00:30.726 --> 00:33.511
They're not even
complaining
about laps!

00:33.598 --> 00:34.686
[BEEPING CONTINUES]
I'll take that.

00:34.773 --> 00:37.211
Thank you very much.
Mine!

00:37.298 --> 00:40.605
Con. Fi. Sca. Ted.

00:40.692 --> 00:41.737
But he just said
his first word!

00:41.824 --> 00:43.521
And his last!

00:43.608 --> 00:44.609
COACH MELLOR:
Your attention please,

00:44.696 --> 00:48.091
place the toys in the bag,
gentlemen and lady.

00:48.178 --> 00:49.179
Was that
really necessary?

00:49.266 --> 00:50.441
You, too?

00:50.528 --> 00:52.704
You're a teacher.
Act like it, damn it!

00:52.791 --> 00:55.055
Actually, Tamagotchis
are very educational.

00:55.142 --> 00:57.448
They teach kids how to be
nurturing and responsible,

00:57.535 --> 00:59.537
kinda like taking care
of a real baby.

00:59.624 --> 01:00.799
I mean, you know
what I'm talking about.

01:00.886 --> 01:02.018
How would I know
what you're talking about?

01:02.105 --> 01:03.498
Well, you're a dad,
right?

01:03.585 --> 01:06.283
I assume...
'Cause you're older.

01:06.370 --> 01:08.068
For your information,
Ringo,

01:08.155 --> 01:10.766
I'm married to that
big, beautiful
gymnasium over there.

01:10.853 --> 01:12.289
Teaching is my life.

01:12.376 --> 01:13.943
I do not have time
for a regular family.

01:14.030 --> 01:16.511
What about every day
after school and weekends

01:16.598 --> 01:19.296
and the 16 weeks a year
that school's not even
in session?

01:19.383 --> 01:21.385
That's it.
I'm confiscating yours, too.

01:21.472 --> 01:22.908
Okay, when it's adults,
it's just stealing.

01:22.995 --> 01:24.301
It's not stealing.
Gimme that.

01:24.388 --> 01:25.694
Get off. Get off it.
I am an adult! I...

01:25.781 --> 01:27.174
Let go of it.
I'll tell the principal.

01:27.261 --> 01:28.305
You want me to tell
the principal?I don't...

01:28.392 --> 01:29.915
The baby...
No!

01:30.002 --> 01:32.309
♪ One of these days
You're gonna get outta here

01:32.396 --> 01:35.269
♪ Live your life
and finally be free

01:35.356 --> 01:38.185
♪ Go where you wanna go
Do what you wanna do

01:38.272 --> 01:42.319
♪ Someday, you will say
"Those were the days" ♪

01:42.406 --> 01:45.061
LAINEY:
It was January 23rd,
1990-something,

01:45.148 --> 01:46.845
and the school bell choir
was on fire

01:46.932 --> 01:49.370
thanks to my star student,
Reed Buccholz.

01:49.457 --> 01:50.806
So, what do you think?

01:50.893 --> 01:53.243
To be honest,
I was expecting
a disaster.

01:53.330 --> 01:55.202
This is not a disaster!

01:55.289 --> 01:57.813
Right? Ah!
I'm so stoked.

01:57.900 --> 01:59.162
Ooh, Reed's solo's
coming up.
Check this out.

01:59.249 --> 02:01.904
[BELLS RINGING]

02:01.991 --> 02:04.254
He's manning
four bells at once.
Can that be done?

02:04.341 --> 02:05.995
Yep.
Reed's my rising star.

02:06.082 --> 02:07.214
He's a natural.

02:07.301 --> 02:08.345
It's like
he's been touched

02:08.432 --> 02:10.565
by the hand of God
himself.

02:10.652 --> 02:12.393
You can pull it back
a little. We're on the
same page here.

02:12.480 --> 02:13.916
I'm really proud
of you, Lainey.

02:14.003 --> 02:15.396
[BELL RINGS]

02:15.483 --> 02:16.353
LAINEY:
You guys are awesome.

02:16.440 --> 02:18.225
Remember, rehearsals
for the recital

02:18.312 --> 02:19.443
start today after school,
okay?

02:19.530 --> 02:21.663
Hey, you killed it
today, Reed.

02:21.750 --> 02:23.360
You're a real "ringer"!
Get it?

02:23.447 --> 02:24.927
Yeah! Kinda.

02:25.014 --> 02:26.798
Anyway, great job.

02:26.885 --> 02:27.886
You're gonna blow
everyone away
at that recital.

02:27.973 --> 02:29.323
About that...

02:29.410 --> 02:30.628
I won't be able to
be in that thing.

02:30.715 --> 02:32.630
Huh?
I can't make it
to rehearsals.

02:32.717 --> 02:34.589
My dad's making me tutor
after every school day.

02:34.676 --> 02:36.547
He's worried that I'm gonna
fail all my AP classes.

02:36.634 --> 02:38.506
You're taking
AP classes?I know!

02:38.593 --> 02:40.421
They're super sucky
and hard.

02:40.508 --> 02:42.205
Unlike this class.
I love ringing bells

02:42.292 --> 02:43.685
'cause anyone can do it,
even me.

02:43.772 --> 02:45.121
Oh, then tell your dad you
wanna ring the bells.

02:45.208 --> 02:46.470
Yeah... No.

02:46.557 --> 02:47.732
You're 14, Reed.

02:47.819 --> 02:49.212
You should be doing
what makes you happy.

02:49.299 --> 02:50.735
I said that.
He doesn't agree.

02:50.822 --> 02:54.609
♪♪

02:54.696 --> 02:56.393
[TIRES SCREECH]

02:56.480 --> 02:58.743
Dad, it is so embarrassing
when you cut
in line like that.

02:58.830 --> 03:01.833
Never be embarrassed
by 457 horsepower, son.

03:01.920 --> 03:03.444
Hi! Hey, Mr. Buccholz.

03:03.531 --> 03:05.489
Can I talk to you for
a second about... Oh.

03:05.576 --> 03:07.317
Wow! That's an
insane-looking car.

03:07.404 --> 03:08.623
Dodge Viper.

03:08.710 --> 03:10.015
It's the deadly snake
of cars.

03:10.102 --> 03:11.800
I'm Lainey Lewis.
I'm Reed's music teacher.

03:11.887 --> 03:13.367
Music?
Yeah.

03:13.454 --> 03:15.412
I-I just wanted
to talk to you...[ENGINE REVS]

03:15.499 --> 03:16.761
Sorry about that.

03:16.848 --> 03:18.285
Powerful engine,
you know?

03:18.372 --> 03:19.503
Can't let it
idle too long.

03:19.590 --> 03:21.766
I know Reed really enjoys
music class.

03:21.853 --> 03:23.203
I have to say...
[ENGINE REVS]

03:23.290 --> 03:24.813
Oh, sorry,
my foot slipped.

03:24.900 --> 03:26.641
Uh, but you were...
Doing this?

03:26.728 --> 03:28.643
I just think
Reed's AP classes

03:28.730 --> 03:29.992
might be way
too challenging
for him and...

03:30.079 --> 03:32.037
[ENGINE REVS]

03:32.124 --> 03:33.691
Are you gonna keep
doing that every time
I say something?

03:33.778 --> 03:35.171
Depends, are you gonna
keep talking about

03:35.258 --> 03:36.303
your silly little
music class?

03:36.390 --> 03:37.608
Yeah.

03:37.695 --> 03:39.610
[ENGINE REVS]
[TIRES SQUEAL]

03:41.090 --> 03:42.439
Oh, you wanna take me on?

03:42.526 --> 03:44.224
Yeah, you have no idea
who you're...

03:44.311 --> 03:46.574
The car's already
a mile away.
Wow, that's fast.

03:46.661 --> 03:48.576
As Reed's dad left me
in his dust,

03:48.663 --> 03:50.491
Coach Mellor arrived
in his office

03:50.578 --> 03:52.754
to the sound
of hundreds of Tamagotchis.

03:52.841 --> 03:54.408
[DEVICES BEEPING]
Oh. [GROANS]

03:55.713 --> 03:56.801
[RATTLING]

03:56.888 --> 03:58.803
Hey, yo!
Help me out!

03:58.890 --> 04:00.544
How do you shut
these Yoshinoyas up?

04:00.631 --> 04:01.676
Tamagotchi?

04:01.763 --> 04:03.112
Yoshinoya's
a fast-food place

04:03.199 --> 04:04.461
I've never known
anybody to go to.

04:04.548 --> 04:05.636
Just...
Stop this beeping
and booping.

04:05.723 --> 04:06.768
It's driving me nuts!

04:06.855 --> 04:09.336
Uh... Okay.
This one's hungry.

04:09.423 --> 04:11.773
It's very simple.
You just hold down this button
and give him food.

04:11.860 --> 04:13.253
Son of a gun.
He ate the food?

04:14.341 --> 04:15.907
Huh.
What's he doing now?

04:15.994 --> 04:17.431
Dancing.
He's happy.

04:17.518 --> 04:18.606
What about this one?

04:18.693 --> 04:21.783
Oh, okay, this one
made a little poopy.

04:21.870 --> 04:23.611
And...
Poopy...

04:23.698 --> 04:25.047
...taken care of.

04:25.134 --> 04:26.918
Ah, poopy's all gone.

04:27.005 --> 04:28.790
What about this one?

04:28.877 --> 04:30.531
Okay,
this one's misbehaving,

04:30.618 --> 04:31.662
so it needs to be
disciplined.

04:31.749 --> 04:33.882
I'll handle this.

04:33.969 --> 04:36.276
[DEVICE BEEPS]

04:36.363 --> 04:37.668
I was tough but fair.

04:37.755 --> 04:39.279
Responded well.
I like that.

04:39.366 --> 04:41.846
Oh, now he's saying,
"I love you."

04:41.933 --> 04:43.587
I love you?
Mmm-hmm.

04:43.674 --> 04:44.675
It's probably 'cause
of the discipline.

04:44.762 --> 04:47.025
You know,
kids need boundaries.Mmm-hmm.

04:47.112 --> 04:48.679
Look at this.
He's waving
at his old man!

04:48.766 --> 04:50.246
Hey.
Pretty cool, right?

04:50.333 --> 04:51.726
Yeah. Get out.

04:51.813 --> 04:52.509
Yep.

04:54.816 --> 05:00.256
"Good evening, parents,
and welcome to... To...

05:00.343 --> 05:01.649
"William Penn Academy."

05:01.736 --> 05:03.694
[SCOFFS] Come on,
John, you know this!

05:03.781 --> 05:04.869
Hey, I gotta talk...
Gah!

05:04.956 --> 05:05.957
What are you doing?

05:06.044 --> 05:07.655
Just practicing
my Parents' Night speech.

05:07.742 --> 05:09.613
Oh, actually,
that's why I'm here.

05:09.700 --> 05:11.398
I need help with
a difficult parent.

05:11.485 --> 05:13.835
There's this obnoxious dad
who's pushing his son
too hard.

05:13.922 --> 05:15.793
The kid is drowning
in his AP classes.

05:15.880 --> 05:17.752
Aww, look at you,
ready to fight like a champ

05:17.839 --> 05:19.449
against some
overbearing parent.

05:19.536 --> 05:20.885
Why are you so happy
about this?

05:20.972 --> 05:23.105
Because this means you're
becoming a real teacher.

05:23.192 --> 05:25.760
Wrangling nasty-ass,
jackhole parents

05:25.847 --> 05:27.544
is the hardest part
of this job.

05:27.631 --> 05:28.980
I didn't realize that.
Yep.

05:29.067 --> 05:31.679
My number one rule is
"The Student Comes First."

05:31.766 --> 05:33.942
But no matter how hard
I try to do that,

05:34.029 --> 05:36.510
I always wind up locking horns
with some dipwad,

05:36.597 --> 05:39.077
douche-bag, bitch-mouth
mother or father.

05:39.164 --> 05:41.210
Well, if this dad wants
a battle, he's got one.

05:41.297 --> 05:43.952
At Parents' Night,
you can straighten him
out face-to-face.

05:44.039 --> 05:45.780
I'm gonna straighten the crap
out of this pushy jerk

05:45.867 --> 05:47.651
and get Reed Buccholz
into my Bell Choir Recital!

05:47.738 --> 05:49.349
Wait, did you say
Reed Buccholz?

05:49.436 --> 05:51.133
Son of Alan Buccholz?
Yeah?

05:51.220 --> 05:53.004
[CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY]
All right, I take it back.

05:53.091 --> 05:55.659
No fighting, no talking,
avoid eye contact.

05:55.746 --> 05:57.661
What? Why?
This is why.

05:57.748 --> 06:00.011
This is gonna be the school's
new computer lab.

06:00.098 --> 06:02.013
Reed's father
is paying for this.

06:02.100 --> 06:03.232
Big deal.
It's made of cardboard.

06:03.319 --> 06:05.103
No, this is just a model.

06:05.190 --> 06:06.757
Look, you saw Reed
in class.

06:06.844 --> 06:08.324
You said he was
touched by God.

06:08.411 --> 06:10.413
And those AP classes
are making him miserable.

06:10.500 --> 06:12.241
We're all miserable
at one time or another.

06:12.328 --> 06:13.982
He can get it out
of the way now.

06:14.069 --> 06:15.549
You just said
your number one rule

06:15.636 --> 06:17.333
is "The Student
Comes First."

06:17.420 --> 06:19.117
I think you're putting
words in my mouth.

06:19.204 --> 06:22.599
You have it written
in old-timey stitching
on your wall!

06:22.686 --> 06:25.123
Okay, look, Lainey,
I have to look
at the big picture,

06:25.210 --> 06:27.517
and that means some parents
you just don't fight.

06:27.604 --> 06:29.432
Oh, so I have to
let Reed suffer

06:29.519 --> 06:31.478
just so the school
can get money?
Is that it?

06:31.565 --> 06:33.871
[CHUCKLES] Thank you
for understanding.

06:33.958 --> 06:35.830
LAINEY: Maybe John
was ignoring his duties,

06:35.917 --> 06:38.528
but Coach took his new responsibility very seriously.

06:38.615 --> 06:41.139
Hey, Coop!
Welcome back, man!

06:41.226 --> 06:43.664
How's the new baby?
Oh, she's beautiful, thanks.

06:43.751 --> 06:46.362
Although I've haven't
slept in two weeks.
[CHUCKLING]

06:46.449 --> 06:47.798
COACH MELLOR:
Tell me about it.

06:47.885 --> 06:50.148
I was up all night with mine.
Feedings, cleaning up poop.

06:50.235 --> 06:51.106
I'm a zombie!

06:51.193 --> 06:53.108
You have a baby, Rick?

06:53.195 --> 06:54.501
Sixty-seven
of the cutest little
buggers you ever saw.

06:54.588 --> 06:55.806
[WHISPERING]
What's he talking about?

06:55.893 --> 06:57.591
I have a hunch,
but I pray I'm wrong.

06:57.678 --> 06:58.766
[DEVICE BEEPING]
Hungry again?

06:58.853 --> 07:01.246
You're gonna eat me out
of house and home, 43.

07:01.333 --> 07:02.030
Okay, not wrong.

07:04.119 --> 07:06.556
You okay, Rick?
I'm better than okay, CB.

07:06.643 --> 07:08.253
I'm A-okay.

07:08.340 --> 07:10.517
And I want to thank you
for showing me who the
real Rick Mellor is,

07:10.604 --> 07:12.997
a loving, nurturing father
locked deep inside

07:13.084 --> 07:14.303
just screaming
to get out.

07:14.390 --> 07:16.218
I showed you how to stop
some toys from beeping.

07:16.305 --> 07:18.220
And my world exploded.

07:18.307 --> 07:20.701
Maybe it'd be
a bit healthier

07:20.788 --> 07:23.878
if you moved on
to nurturing
something real?

07:23.965 --> 07:25.314
What do you mean "real"?

07:25.401 --> 07:27.272
Like an actual eating,
breathing, living organism?

07:27.359 --> 07:28.839
You're right! A baby!

07:28.926 --> 07:30.798
No! A turtle.
I was gonna say turtle.

07:30.885 --> 07:32.843
I want to thank you
for showing me my true path.

07:32.930 --> 07:34.279
Rick Mellor
is gonna have a baby.

07:34.366 --> 07:37.239
Okay, to be very clear,
that's not at all
what I said.

07:37.326 --> 07:39.502
Thank you for being
my rock, Charlie B.

07:39.589 --> 07:41.591
Charlie.
I like that name.

07:41.678 --> 07:43.332
It works for a girl
or a boy.

07:43.419 --> 07:45.682
Please don't name
the baby after me.
Or have one at all.

07:45.769 --> 07:47.989
Little Charlie Mellor!
It's got a nice ring
to it, huh?

07:48.076 --> 07:49.425
You do know that you need
someone else to have a baby.

07:49.512 --> 07:51.340
A woman.
Not a problem.

07:51.427 --> 07:53.211
Well, meeting
the right person
takes time,

07:53.298 --> 07:55.692
and you work so much...
Of course.

07:55.779 --> 07:59.000
I'll just choose somebody
who works at William Penn.

07:59.087 --> 08:00.871
You are full of good ideas,
my friend.

08:00.958 --> 08:03.961
No, please don't shop
for a baby mama
on the faculty!

08:04.048 --> 08:07.138
Who knew? The mother
of my future child
walks amongst us!

08:07.225 --> 08:11.186
Please reconsider
the turtle!I shan't!

08:11.273 --> 08:13.101
LAINEY: Coach decided it was time to start a family,

08:13.188 --> 08:15.016
and he wasn't going
to waste any time.

08:15.103 --> 08:17.148
Morning, CB.
Oh, no.

08:17.235 --> 08:19.063
Uh, Rick, Rick,
what's happening here?

08:19.150 --> 08:21.152
Why are you wearing
little-boy church clothes?

08:21.239 --> 08:23.851
Follow me and watch
your vision become
a reality, my friend.

08:23.938 --> 08:25.505
No, I have no vision.
No vision.

08:25.592 --> 08:27.942
What are you doing?
Stop! What are you doing?

08:28.029 --> 08:30.335
I'm gonna walk into that
teachers lounge alone

08:30.422 --> 08:32.773
and walk out with
the mother of my child.Rick!

08:32.860 --> 08:34.078
You can't just tell
a group of ladies

08:34.165 --> 08:35.689
one of them needs to make
a baby with you.

08:35.776 --> 08:37.473
You're right.
I should ask.

08:38.692 --> 08:40.607
As always,
you got my back.

08:42.913 --> 08:44.349
Excuse me!

08:44.436 --> 08:47.309
I have a business proposition
for all female staff

08:47.396 --> 08:48.702
with healthy
reproductive organs.

08:48.789 --> 08:49.790
I'm so sorry.

08:49.877 --> 08:52.357
I have decided
to procreate,

08:52.444 --> 08:54.098
thanks to the advice
of Big Charlie here.

08:54.185 --> 08:56.274
And so, I'm looking for
a partner who can help me

08:56.361 --> 08:58.538
bring forth the next
generation of Mellor.

08:58.625 --> 09:01.279
And after it's born...
Well, who knows.

09:01.366 --> 09:03.673
I guess we'll figure
it out on the fly.

09:03.760 --> 09:05.066
So!

09:05.153 --> 09:06.328
Who's interested?

09:06.415 --> 09:09.070
♪♪

09:10.550 --> 09:12.073
Nobody?

09:12.160 --> 09:13.596
Shocking.

09:13.683 --> 09:15.685
I can give you my answer.

09:15.772 --> 09:17.513
Your proposal
is sexist,
misogynist,

09:17.600 --> 09:18.688
infantile, and ludicrous.

09:20.385 --> 09:21.386
And I accept.

09:21.473 --> 09:23.127
Okay, what is happening
right now?

09:23.214 --> 09:24.781
I'll tell you
what's happening.

09:24.868 --> 09:26.827
I just became
the happiest man on Earth.

09:28.655 --> 09:29.743
Oh.
Ah.

09:29.830 --> 09:31.005
Sorry.

09:31.092 --> 09:32.702
Eh.

09:32.789 --> 09:34.574
♪♪

09:34.661 --> 09:36.663
[WHISPERING] A baby.

09:36.750 --> 09:38.752
LAINEY: It was Parents' Night,

09:38.839 --> 09:40.971
and even though Glascott
told me not to challenge
Reed's dad,

09:41.058 --> 09:43.452
I couldn't just step aside
when it came to helping
a student.

09:43.539 --> 09:46.150
Alan. Alan Buccholz.
Hi. Lainey Lewis.

09:46.237 --> 09:48.196
We met the other day
when you almost
ran over my foot?

09:48.283 --> 09:50.198
Uh...

09:50.285 --> 09:52.287
No, nothing.

09:52.374 --> 09:54.419
I thought Parents' Night
would be a good time
to talk about my class.

09:54.506 --> 09:56.726
Okay, well,
consider it talked about.

09:56.813 --> 09:58.946
Now, if you'll excuse me,
I'm going to move on
to some classes

09:59.033 --> 10:00.556
that colleges
actually care about.

10:00.643 --> 10:02.689
Well, that's a shame,
'cause your son is failing.

10:02.776 --> 10:04.865
What, hey!
Failing? Come here!

10:04.952 --> 10:06.606
Hold on, now.
Wait a second.
What was that?

10:06.693 --> 10:08.651
Ah, it's fine.
Head on over
to the real classes.

10:08.738 --> 10:12.263
Oh, come on.
Ple... Is it even
possible to fail music?

10:12.350 --> 10:13.917
[CHUCKLING]
I mean, really.

10:14.004 --> 10:15.789
Do-re-mi,
hey-bop-a-ree-bop.

10:15.876 --> 10:17.573
See?
I just got an A.

10:17.660 --> 10:20.271
For Reed to pass,
he has to perform
in the bells recital,

10:20.358 --> 10:23.274
which he can't do
'cause he's so overwhelmed
by all the AP classes.

10:23.361 --> 10:25.233
Of course
he's overwhelmed!

10:25.320 --> 10:27.670
I'm grooming him
to take over my business!

10:27.757 --> 10:30.586
He's gonna make
a lot more money
as a CEO than a, what?

10:30.673 --> 10:32.370
A... A town crier?

10:32.457 --> 10:34.111
[CHUCKLES]
"Hear ye, hear ye!"

10:34.198 --> 10:37.941
Those guys make about
40 grand a year, tops.
Tops!

10:38.028 --> 10:40.727
Your son loves my class.
Don't you care
if he's happy?

10:40.814 --> 10:43.599
He's a kid!
He's supposed to
be miserable!

10:43.686 --> 10:45.340
Hey, hey, hey,
what's going on?

10:45.427 --> 10:47.821
Your teacher here is trying
to make my son happy!

10:47.908 --> 10:49.300
Well, why would you do
something like that?

10:49.387 --> 10:51.825
Because you said,
"The student comes first!"

10:51.912 --> 10:56.177
No, uh, you have me confused
with some confused idiot
who says stupid stuff.

10:56.264 --> 10:57.961
You and I need to have
a serious discussion

10:58.048 --> 11:00.834
about the Alan T. Buccholz
Computer Lab.

11:00.921 --> 11:02.357
9:00 a.m. sharp,
your office.

11:04.489 --> 11:06.840
You see?
That's why I told you
not to get involved.

11:06.927 --> 11:09.407
Now I gotta deal with
an angry parent man.

11:09.494 --> 11:10.844
Isn't that
your entire job?

11:10.931 --> 11:13.194
No! Most of it.

11:13.281 --> 11:15.370
All I wanted was to do what's
best for the students.

11:15.457 --> 11:17.111
Call me crazy, but I thought
that's what we were here for.

11:19.374 --> 11:21.332
I've looked into many
fertility options,

11:21.419 --> 11:23.683
but they're so expensive
and impersonal.

11:23.770 --> 11:25.075
Your timing was excellent.

11:25.162 --> 11:27.338
Well, we've both wound up
childless over 40,

11:27.425 --> 11:29.123
so might as well
team up, right?

11:29.210 --> 11:31.386
I am childless
because I choose
to be childless,

11:31.473 --> 11:34.128
and I am over 40 because
I choose to be over 40.

11:34.215 --> 11:35.433
Fine.

11:35.520 --> 11:37.479
Now, there are multiple items
we need to agree on.

11:37.566 --> 11:39.002
First off, conception.

11:39.089 --> 11:40.874
There's obviously
the artificial way,

11:40.961 --> 11:42.876
and then, of course,
there's the natural...

11:42.963 --> 11:44.312
Artificial.
You sure?

11:44.399 --> 11:45.922
[WHISPERING] Artificial.
All right, then!

11:46.009 --> 11:47.837
Next, I will be
cocooning the baby

11:47.924 --> 11:49.578
for the first six months
on my chest

11:49.665 --> 11:51.580
to approximate
the feeling of the uterus.

11:51.667 --> 11:53.103
I want to do that, too.

11:53.190 --> 11:55.627
Oh, I'm sorry,
do you have a uterus
that I don't know about?

11:55.715 --> 11:58.021
Well, fine,
but you can cocoon the baby
and I'll cocoon you.

11:58.108 --> 11:59.327
What do you weigh,
about a buck 50?

11:59.414 --> 12:01.590
No man will
cocoon me, sir!I can!

12:01.677 --> 12:03.157
I'll wrap you up
and carry you around

12:03.244 --> 12:04.680
as you carry
the baby around!

12:04.767 --> 12:07.770
Okay, you can't cocoon someone
who's cocooning someone else!

12:07.857 --> 12:09.729
I think maybe we let
the baby's godfather

12:09.816 --> 12:11.295
make the call
on this one.

12:11.382 --> 12:13.080
Don't want to be
the godfather.

12:13.167 --> 12:14.385
Well, who's gonna
raise the baby

12:14.472 --> 12:16.039
if Liz and I both go down
in a plane crash?

12:16.126 --> 12:18.302
I'm sorry, where would we
be flying together?

12:18.389 --> 12:20.261
The Bahamas.
It was gonna be a surprise.

12:20.348 --> 12:22.350
I'm fair-skinned.
We'll rent a cabana!

12:22.437 --> 12:25.005
Can we please stay on the
subject of raising the child?

12:25.092 --> 12:27.181
Please.
I will be raising
the child.

12:27.268 --> 12:29.270
You can visit at
prearranged times.

12:29.357 --> 12:31.098
No unscheduled pop-ins.

12:31.185 --> 12:33.187
But Little Charlie
needs to know
that his daddy's nearby!

12:33.274 --> 12:34.449
I'm sorry,
who's Little Charlie?

12:34.536 --> 12:35.929
It's the baby's name!
After CB over here.

12:36.016 --> 12:37.365
Oh,
that's actually quite nice.

12:37.452 --> 12:38.627
It works
for a boy or a girl.

12:38.714 --> 12:40.063
That you agree on?

12:40.150 --> 12:42.805
No, actually,
we don't agree on anything.

12:42.892 --> 12:44.633
Rick, I thought this
was just going to be

12:44.720 --> 12:48.724
a business transaction
between two co-workers
in a teachers lounge.

12:48.811 --> 12:51.292
I don't understand
how such a simple idea
got so complicated.

12:51.379 --> 12:53.424
I don't know.
I thought maybe,
you know,

12:53.511 --> 12:56.210
we'd be kind of
like a family.

12:56.297 --> 12:58.603
[DEVICE BEEPING]
What is that?

12:58.690 --> 13:01.258
That's my Tamagotchi,
although I've never heard it
make that noise before.

13:01.345 --> 13:02.346
That means it died.

13:03.957 --> 13:04.958
Died?

13:05.045 --> 13:06.350
It's dead.

13:06.437 --> 13:08.962
♪♪

13:09.049 --> 13:10.398
You can't even
take care of a toy.

13:12.400 --> 13:14.184
[SIGHS] This isn't
going to work.
I'm sorry.

13:15.577 --> 13:16.926
[SIGHS]

13:17.013 --> 13:18.406
♪♪

13:22.062 --> 13:23.585
Hey, John?
Gah!

13:23.672 --> 13:26.762
[SIGHS] Come on,
stop that.Sorry.

13:26.849 --> 13:29.156
And I'm sorry
for the timing of
my blow-up last night.

13:29.243 --> 13:30.679
Well, I appreciate that.

13:30.766 --> 13:33.160
But I am definitely
not sorry
for trying to...

13:33.247 --> 13:35.118
"Work Hard Play Hard"?

13:35.205 --> 13:36.119
You took down
"The Student Comes First"?

13:36.206 --> 13:37.686
No.

13:37.773 --> 13:39.209
I know it
was there, John.

13:39.296 --> 13:42.038
Look, I have to give in to
Alan for this computer lab.

13:42.125 --> 13:44.432
So where do you
draw the line, John?

13:44.519 --> 13:46.477
Does a parent get
to call the shots

13:46.564 --> 13:48.436
because they
give the school
a new minivan,

13:48.523 --> 13:50.568
a few tether balls,
a box of chalk?

13:50.655 --> 13:51.874
A new minivan.

13:51.961 --> 13:54.007
Look, I know.
You're right.

13:54.094 --> 13:57.488
I wish that I was stronger
dealing with mean,
entitled parents,

13:57.575 --> 13:59.186
but that's the thing
that I am the worst at.

13:59.273 --> 14:01.101
Well, you better start
learning how to handle this,

14:01.188 --> 14:03.364
'cause it's gonna
happen over and over.But how?

14:03.451 --> 14:06.628
I don't know if you know this,
but I get sweaty
and flustered very easily.

14:06.715 --> 14:10.066
What if I told you
I had a foolproof way
for you to stand strong

14:10.153 --> 14:12.895
and always have the exact,
perfect words to say?

14:12.982 --> 14:14.157
I'd say that
I'm intrigued.

14:14.244 --> 14:16.551
The only way to fight
a difficult parent

14:16.638 --> 14:19.336
is with the most
difficult parent
this school has ever seen.

14:19.423 --> 14:21.599
Don't say it...
A woman whose
overbearing smotherhood

14:21.686 --> 14:24.646
is still legendary
a decade later.Don't say it!

14:24.733 --> 14:26.691
Beverly Goldberg.

14:26.778 --> 14:28.693
I said don't say it!

14:28.780 --> 14:30.347
We both know she's
the best shot you have
at fighting fire with fire.

14:30.434 --> 14:33.046
Fine.

14:33.133 --> 14:36.049
Okay. Let's dance
with the devil.
Summon her.

14:36.136 --> 14:38.225
I'm already here!
Aah!

14:38.312 --> 14:40.618
♪♪

14:40.705 --> 14:43.491
LAINEY: Glascott
needed help dealing
with a difficult parent,

14:43.578 --> 14:44.927
so I brought in
my secret weapon.

14:45.014 --> 14:46.015
Well, there's nothing
I hate more

14:46.102 --> 14:48.104
than a demanding,
bossy parent

14:48.191 --> 14:51.064
with unrealistic expectations
for their schmoopy.

14:51.151 --> 14:53.153
[CHUCKLES]
So, what's the plan?

14:53.240 --> 14:57.374
Oh. We're gonna put your words
in John's mouth using this.

14:57.461 --> 14:59.855
It's called
an America Online
chat session.

14:59.942 --> 15:01.422
Whatever scathing things
you type here

15:01.509 --> 15:03.685
will appear on John's
computer screen in there.

15:03.772 --> 15:05.774
He'll sneak a look
and say what you wrote.

15:05.861 --> 15:07.428
[GASPS] Oh, my God!
Alan is coming!

15:07.515 --> 15:08.777
Lainey, hide! He hates you!

15:08.864 --> 15:10.561
Hey there, good sir!

15:10.648 --> 15:12.694
Let's make this quick.
I'm flying to lunch
in a half hour.

15:12.781 --> 15:14.174
[CHUCKLING] Okay.

15:16.089 --> 15:17.786
So, it's, uh,
a beautiful morning.

15:17.873 --> 15:19.962
Can I offer you
a cup of co...Here's the deal.

15:20.049 --> 15:22.443
Fire the music teacher
and you got yourself
a computer lab.

15:22.530 --> 15:23.444
[WHISPERING] He wants
a teacher fired?

15:23.531 --> 15:25.141
That's my move!

15:25.228 --> 15:26.708
And I know just
what I'd say, too.

15:26.795 --> 15:28.536
I'd say, "I am the principal
of this school.

15:28.623 --> 15:30.886
"You don't get to tell me
who to fire, [BLEEP]-face!"

15:30.973 --> 15:32.583
Type it!
Oh. Right. Okay.

15:32.670 --> 15:34.237
Uh...

15:34.324 --> 15:35.412
I...

15:35.499 --> 15:36.370
[COMPUTER BEEPS]

15:37.240 --> 15:38.154
I...

15:40.200 --> 15:41.027
You what?

15:42.898 --> 15:44.856
[SINGSONG VOICE]
Ba-ba-ba-ba,
ba-ba-ba, ba-ba-ba.

15:44.944 --> 15:47.381
[NORMAL VOICE] This keyboard
is not the same as the
keyboard I have at home.

15:47.468 --> 15:49.296
I'm sorry.
Well, that's impossible.

15:49.383 --> 15:51.167
We're the apostrophe?
I want to spell "I'm."

15:51.254 --> 15:52.299
It's there!

15:54.562 --> 15:55.824
[BEEP]

15:55.911 --> 15:57.434
I'm...

15:57.521 --> 15:59.306
Stay off the top line!
That's only numbers!

15:59.393 --> 16:02.744
I'm 7...

16:02.831 --> 16:03.701
Is that a 7?

16:05.399 --> 16:08.750
"I'm 7% colon."
I'm 7% colon.

16:08.837 --> 16:10.186
Well, I'm 8%.

16:10.273 --> 16:11.318
Doctor checked it
last month.

16:11.405 --> 16:12.797
Said it's the most colon
he's ever seen.

16:15.148 --> 16:16.888
Four...
How do I erase?

16:16.976 --> 16:17.977
Nope.

16:18.064 --> 16:19.761
Oh, poop.

16:19.848 --> 16:21.371
Well, this is a stupid
and bizarre waste of time,

16:21.458 --> 16:23.112
so you just lost yourself
a computer lab.

16:23.199 --> 16:25.114
Damn it. Fine.

16:25.201 --> 16:27.073
Well, at least we still
have this one.

16:27.160 --> 16:28.378
Nope, I'm taking
that one, too.Ohh!

16:28.465 --> 16:29.727
All right, fine!

16:29.814 --> 16:31.555
You know what, you can take
all of your computer labs,

16:31.642 --> 16:34.036
but I will not fire
Lainey Lewis.

16:34.123 --> 16:36.125
In fact, I wish I had
more teachers like her.

16:36.212 --> 16:38.606
Not a lot more...
Maybe one.

16:38.693 --> 16:39.868
You know why?

16:39.955 --> 16:41.609
Because she puts
the students first.

16:41.696 --> 16:44.960
If Reed is not at her recital,
she will fail him.

16:45.047 --> 16:46.309
Did you type
that for him?

16:46.396 --> 16:47.397
Not a word.

16:47.484 --> 16:49.269
I couldn't have.
There's no "H."

16:49.356 --> 16:51.010
Are you telling me
to shove it?

16:51.097 --> 16:54.491
Nnnnn...

16:54.578 --> 16:55.623
Yes.

16:55.710 --> 16:57.625
Well, all right.

16:57.712 --> 16:59.931
My son can ring the bells.

17:00.019 --> 17:01.933
Not because you're right,

17:02.021 --> 17:03.587
but because he needs
straight A's
to get into Princeton.

17:03.674 --> 17:05.328
Thank you.

17:05.415 --> 17:06.895
And if it makes
any difference,

17:06.982 --> 17:09.289
this is really gonna
make him a happy kid.

17:09.376 --> 17:11.552
What is it with you all
wanting kids to be happy?

17:11.639 --> 17:13.945
Huh? Enough!

17:14.033 --> 17:15.295
My God!

17:15.382 --> 17:17.210
♪♪

17:17.297 --> 17:18.646
I guess my job
here is done.

17:18.733 --> 17:20.169
You did nothing.

17:20.256 --> 17:21.736
And everything.

17:21.823 --> 17:22.563
You're welcome.

17:22.650 --> 17:24.913
♪♪

17:25.000 --> 17:27.742
LAINEY: Coach Mellor's
dream of being a father
had disappeared,

17:27.829 --> 17:29.526
and now he couldn't bear
to hold on to

17:29.613 --> 17:31.746
the tiny, electric reminders
of what he had lost.

17:31.833 --> 17:34.270
I'm sorry, Ed.
He didn't make it.

17:34.357 --> 17:35.706
Huh?
It's my fault.

17:35.793 --> 17:37.795
Although, I don't know
why I thought

17:37.882 --> 17:39.058
I could take care
of anything.

17:39.145 --> 17:40.755
Oh.
Sure. Whatever.

17:42.800 --> 17:44.846
So, giving 'em all back?

17:44.933 --> 17:48.502
Yeah, although, most of the
kids don't seem to want 'em.

17:48.589 --> 17:50.504
Something called Pogs
is sweeping the nation.

17:50.591 --> 17:52.767
Yeah, it's a game you play
with these things.

17:52.854 --> 17:53.985
We can give it a shot when
you're feeling better.

17:54.073 --> 17:55.900
Nah.
It's funny, eh.

17:55.987 --> 17:58.425
My whole life, I thought
all I wanted to be
was a teacher.

17:58.512 --> 18:00.470
And now I realize
I want to be a dad,

18:00.557 --> 18:02.516
but it may not be
in the cards for me.

18:02.603 --> 18:03.952
Rick, you are a dad.

18:04.039 --> 18:05.693
To every single kid
in this school.

18:05.780 --> 18:08.565
That's different.
It's not that different.

18:08.652 --> 18:11.351
You not only teach these kids,
you inspire them, man.

18:11.438 --> 18:13.614
You show them that if
they believe in you,

18:13.701 --> 18:16.182
if they believe in themselves,
anything is possible.

18:16.269 --> 18:17.966
Thanks, CB.

18:18.053 --> 18:21.448
Now get back to work
and be a dad to these kids
right here.

18:21.535 --> 18:23.319
Maybe one day,
the right person
will notice.

18:24.799 --> 18:26.105
[SIGHS]

18:26.192 --> 18:27.889
♪ Backbeat, the word
is on the street

18:27.976 --> 18:31.545
♪ That the fire
in your heart is out

18:31.632 --> 18:33.590
♪ I'm sure you've
heard it all before

18:33.677 --> 18:36.071
♪ But you never really
had a doubt

18:36.158 --> 18:38.769
Well, what do you think?

18:38.856 --> 18:42.773
I think the little
knucklehead looks happy.

18:42.860 --> 18:44.819
♪ Feels the way I do
about you now

18:44.906 --> 18:46.951
I know you think he needs
to end up just like you.

18:47.038 --> 18:48.736
And maybe he will.

18:48.823 --> 18:51.304
But for now, I think
he's doing pretty good
just being him.

18:51.391 --> 18:53.001
[BELLS RINGING]

18:54.959 --> 18:56.787
[CHEERS AND APPLAUSE]

18:56.874 --> 18:58.180
♪♪

18:59.747 --> 19:01.705
♪ Today was gonna be the day

19:01.792 --> 19:03.359
♪ But they'll never
throw it back to you

19:03.446 --> 19:06.449
You know, I used to play
a pretty mean trombone
when I was a kid.

19:06.536 --> 19:07.972
Really?
Mmm-hmm.

19:08.059 --> 19:08.930
So why'd you stop?

19:09.017 --> 19:10.932
Eh, Grandpa made me.

19:11.019 --> 19:13.021
Dude, he sucks.

19:13.108 --> 19:15.154
Yeah, he really does.

19:17.286 --> 19:18.809
You know, when
I started this job,

19:18.896 --> 19:21.203
you said even though
we don't get paid much
and the hours suck,

19:21.290 --> 19:22.944
there would be moments
that would make
it all worth it.

19:23.945 --> 19:25.251
You were right.

19:25.338 --> 19:26.817
Well, enjoy it.

19:26.904 --> 19:29.037
I know I used to.
Used to?

19:29.124 --> 19:31.953
Before I became Principal,
I always looked down on
the administration

19:32.040 --> 19:34.434
because money
was their only priority.

19:35.261 --> 19:36.610
And now look at me.

19:36.697 --> 19:38.264
Come on, you did
the right thing in the end.

19:38.351 --> 19:40.614
Only 'cause you
got me there.So?

19:40.701 --> 19:43.138
A few months ago,
I was broke and desperate.

19:43.225 --> 19:46.185
But thanks to you,
I ended up here.

19:46.272 --> 19:47.751
Doesn't matter how you get
somewhere as long as you do.

19:47.838 --> 19:49.188
Hmm.

19:50.058 --> 19:51.755
Thank you.

19:51.842 --> 19:53.627
But yeah, next time,
show some balls

19:53.714 --> 19:54.845
so we don't have to call
Beverly Goldberg.

19:54.932 --> 19:56.412
Oh, God, no.

19:56.499 --> 19:58.414
♪ I said maybe

19:58.501 --> 20:00.547
I know you can do this!
There it is!

20:00.634 --> 20:01.635
Splay your hands!

20:01.722 --> 20:02.853
[WHISTLE BLOWS]
Yes!

20:02.940 --> 20:05.116
Oh!
Oh!

20:05.204 --> 20:06.292
LAINEY: Sometimes our lives
don't turn out exactly
like we'd planned.

20:06.379 --> 20:08.337
That's what
I'm talking about!
Good stuff!

20:08.424 --> 20:10.557
We often find ourselves
in places we never
thought we'd be.

20:10.644 --> 20:13.734
♪ You're my wonderwall

20:13.821 --> 20:16.519
But if we take the time
to look around

20:16.606 --> 20:18.129
to see the good
we do for others...

20:18.217 --> 20:20.219
♪ I said maybe ♪

20:22.308 --> 20:25.267
...how we teach them,
inspire them,

20:25.354 --> 20:27.356
and give them the tools to be
the best they can be...

20:27.443 --> 20:30.054
♪♪

20:30.141 --> 20:32.796
...we may find that
the reality of our lives

20:32.883 --> 20:34.581
exceeds all of our
expectations.

20:34.668 --> 20:36.235
♪♪

20:40.848 --> 20:43.590
Hi, I'm Liz Fleming.
And I'm the real
Liz Flemming.

20:43.677 --> 20:45.331
All right, Liz,
get real with me.

20:45.418 --> 20:48.464
Uh, what are the politics
of the teachers lounge?

20:48.551 --> 20:49.813
What goes on behind
closed doors?

20:49.900 --> 20:51.598
There's a fair amount
of complaining.

20:51.685 --> 20:52.773
[LAUGHS]

20:52.860 --> 20:54.340
Um, complaining
about faculty meetings

20:54.427 --> 20:57.473
or administrative decisions
or about specific students.

20:57.560 --> 20:59.258
So what goes on in
the teachers lounge...

20:59.345 --> 21:00.650
Stays in
the teachers lounge.

21:00.737 --> 21:03.784
How do you deal with, like,
a really tough parent?

21:03.871 --> 21:05.873
I try to kill them
with kindness,

21:05.960 --> 21:07.483
and I've been lucky.

21:07.570 --> 21:10.573
Maybe it's your, uh,
gentle, stoic calm?

21:10.660 --> 21:12.880
Definitely.
[LAUGHS]

21:12.967 --> 21:14.447
So, speaking of
difficult parents,

21:14.534 --> 21:17.101
what was it like working with
the real Beverly Goldberg?

21:17.188 --> 21:19.582
She was one of the ones
who liked me.[LAUGHS]

21:19.669 --> 21:22.411
Um, I think I gave Adam
good enough grades
that she was okay.

21:22.498 --> 21:25.458
And so I was one of
the rare lucky ones, I think.

21:25.545 --> 21:26.502
[LAUGHS]
